{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480924"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:53:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:53:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"126"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/126"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.04,0.21,0.62,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"126"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44070"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/126"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"126"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29051"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"121"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2255"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2289"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44070"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with haematuria, weight loss and night sweats, and is subsequently diagnosed with a left renal cell carcinoma on CT scan. The tumour is a 4.5 cm exophytic mass and there is no evidence of local invasion or metastatic spread. He has a medical history of poorly-controlled diabetes, obstructive sleep apnoea, hypertension, paroxysmal atrial fibrillation, and a previous myocardial infarction. His medications include perindopril, warfarin, aspirin, and clopidogrel. On examination, his vitals are within normal limits and his BMI is 43 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Cardiorespiratory assessment reveals an irregularly irregular pulse and an ejection click systolic murmur heard loudest in the second intercostal space, right sternal edge.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chemotherapy","Immunotherapy","Observation with surveillance imaging","Anaesthetic review to see if fit for surgery","Radical nephrectomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has numerous co-morbitidies; diabetes, past myocardial infarction, obesity, atrial fibrillation and a likely aortic stenosis on physical examination, all of which are significant and make him a possibly poor surgical candidate. Thus, although a \u003Cstrong\u003Eradical nephrectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is an appropriate treatment option in a surgically fit patient, this patient first needs \u003Cstrong\u003Eanaesthetic review to see if he is fit for surgery.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is most often ineffective in renal cell carcinoma, and is not a treatment modality as a result.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmunotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is becoming more widely used in metastatic renal cell carcinoma, it is not first-line treatment for local disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation with surveillance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if he is not fit for anaesthetic.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Surgical management is first-line for non-metastatic renal cell carcinoma."],"references":["Gray RE, Harris GT. Renal Cell Carcinoma: Diagnosis and Management. Am Fam Physician. 2019; 99:179-84. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30702258/","Deleuze A, Saout J, Dugay F, Peyronnet B, Mathieu R, Verhoest G, et al. Immunotherapy in Renal Cell Carcinoma: The Future Is Now. Int J Mol Sci. 2020;21(7):2532. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7177761/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29051"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"126"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29051"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-06T12:07:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-06T12:07:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"126"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44070"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/121"},"attributes":{